Djp is a parser and an emacs mode for Java version 7.

The emacs mode provides only two features:

- syntax highlighting
- indentation


Emacs mode (djp-mode) installation
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

0) Install the Boost library

    Fedora:
    su -c 'yum install boost-devel'

    Ubuntu:
    sudo apt-get install libboost-dev

    OSX:
    sudo port install boost

1) Checkout the code.
    git clone git://github.com/dberg/djp.git

2) Build it
    cd djp/src
    make BUILDTYPE=Release

3) Open the file /src/djp-mode/djp-mode.el and set the variable
    'djp-executable' to 'PATH/TO/src/out/Release/bin/djp'.

4) Add the following to your .emacs file:
    (add-to-list 'load-path "~/PATH/TO/src/djp-mode")
    (autoload 'djp-mode "djp-mode" "Major mode for Java." t)
    (add-to-list 'auto-mode-alist '("\\.java$" . djp-mode))


Parser lib
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The parser from djp is modular and can be embedded into different projects. The
directory 'sample' includes a simple example that takes the following java
class as input:

Class Foo {
    public Foo() {}
    public String bar() { return ""; }
    public void baz() {}
}

and prints a list of method names found int the class Foo:

Foo
  Foo (constructor)
  bar
  baz

To build and execute the sample code:

  cd djp/src
  make
  cd sample
  make
  ./out/Debug/bin/ListClassMethods
